latestPosts.caption:
The 35 meter blue taffeta gown made for sangeet / cocktail evening by @howareyoufeeling.studio By-appointment.

A surrealistic approach to the evening @akshaara_ writes beautifully.. 

“The Sangeet and The Cocktail, which was their take on surrealism getting a bit out of proportion, out of their minds into dreams and the unreal. Both Joshi and Balser’s outfits were a nod to their favourite art movement – surrealism, inspired by the works of Elsa Schepirelli. Joshi’s dress was her own, made of blue taffeta using nearly thirty five meters of fabric that created the illusion of the sea, from which emerged a large mother of pearl that sat on the chest, paired with earrings from Swarovski and rings from Schiaparelli.” - for @vogueindia 

I found the mother of pearl in johari bazaar from an older fellow selling sweet nothings on the street. We both ran a hard bargain, but we both won in the end ;) The blue ( in hindi Neil ) sea of fabric was then amusingly fitting ! 

Painstakingly assisted in the making @nishthajainn & @joshi_g_l_ to find a way to have it float/ sit on the chest ( dad duties ) 
Styled by @anchalnotani 
Makeup by @sculpt.ing_ 
Photos  @eshantrajuphotography 
3rd photo @ryantandya / Art directed by @fraymondh

We were delighted to welcome some very special guests to the seaside last Friday for a Brighton Festival Field Trip hosted by @diet_paratha and 2025 Festival Guest Director @anoushkashankarofficial .

Guests received a private viewing of @doyeljoshi and @neilghosebalser ’s (@howareyoufeeling.studio ) beautiful red chair installation at the Brighton Bandstand, followed by a gourmet meal at Cecconi’s at Brighton Beach House and panel discussion from Anoushka, Doyel and Neil.

Huge thanks to Taranjit Goodwin, Diet Paratha, Anoushka, Doyel and Neil, @sohohouse Brighton and all our special guests for such a wonderful day.

Ready to celebrate with us at an epic Brighton Festival 2025 finale? Anoushka and Shiva Soundsystem founder @nerm have curated an unmissable lineup of friends and special guests to hit the decks for The Official Brighton Festival Closing Party, Sun 25 May in the beautiful @brighton_dome Corn Exchange.

Book now on our website and get ready to dance the night away!

Photography: Rio Carciero 

#BrightonFestival

latestPosts.caption:
This weekend, as part of the @brightonfestival with guest curator @anoushkashankarofficial , we will be showing our final exhibit from 23-26th at The Old Courtroom in Brighton. 

108 red monoblock chairs have been showing up in different locations in Brighton as a traveling installation and foreshadowing of the upcoming exhibit.
We invited the public to sit, pause, observe, and listen in. Inspired by Anoushka Shankar’s album and the festival theme ‘New Dawn’, 108 Chairs reflects cycles of nature and humanity, speaking to where hope takes root. 
.. 
Opening times:

Fri 23 May, 12-4pm 
Sat 24 & 25 May, 10am-6pm 
Mon 26 May, 10am-4pm 

@brightonfestival @anoushkashankarofficial

Photo & Video @suryansaurabh

“Gond is a humble material that has so far always played an invisible role in various aspects of everyday life in Rajasthan, from an ingredient in food to a binding agent for stone pigments used in miniature paintings. In the front of house, one never saw what it looked like because it always blended in quietly with more main character energy foods in the kitchens behind closed doors — without fuss, doing its job and leaving no visible trace of its existence. Doyel and Neil now bring this modest material to the forefront, elevating its presence as a sculpture against white walls. The work stands almost as if it floats and hovers above its pedestal, suspended in mid-air. On one side, drops of Gond seem frozen in time and space, like ice popsicles preserved beneath a glacier or inside an icy cave. On the other side, it exhibits a smooth shine, as if its viscosity allows it to be poured gently onto the surface — quite the opposite of how the material truly behaves.” - Ayesha Parikh, gallerist at Art and Charlie, Mumbai

This work is the first in a larger series by the artist duo using this material.

Gond (2025) — a new series of sculptural works by @doyeljoshi and @neilghosebalser.
Presented at @jaipurcentreforart by @whitewall.art @pachojaipur.
Curated by @noellekadar.
Supported by @artandcharlie 

*****
@bose.krishnamachari recently shared his impressions of the exhibition at @jaipurcentreforart :
“I was in Jaipur today to witness the brilliant show “(In Dia)logue: Tradition & Transformation” #curated by @noellekadar at the Jaipur Centre for Art @jaipurcentreforart . It was inspiring to see how the city becomes a living canvas—hosting artists and institutions working collectively to celebrate and interrogate cultural inheritance.

The exhibition, presented by Whitewall Magazine, is a layered portrayal of contemporary India—its multiplicity, memory, and momentum. Collaborations with key art spaces like @artandcharlie , Experimenter, IRAM Art, @jhavericontemporary #NatureMorte, @rajivmenoncontemporary and #VadehraGallery make this a truly collective moment.” 
Photo credit : @bose.krishnamachari

latestPosts.caption:
@doyeljoshi and @neilghosebalser of Mumbai based @howareyoufeeling.studio are the incredible artists and couple behind the four Brighton Festival 2025 brochure covers.

They are also the creators of the city-wide art project and traveling pop-up installation, How dark it is before dawn, running throughout the Festival. Finally, this participatory act culminates in a major exhibition at The Old Court Room 24-27 May.

We caught up with them about how they created the brochure covers and how you can get involved in How dark it is before dawn - link in bio.

Fallen in love with this year's Brighton Festival covers? Buy a print of Doyel and Neil's New Dawn artworks, or your favourite classic Brighton Festival artworks over at @kingandmcgaw .

📸 Our CEO @lucy_alexandra_davies , @anoushkashankarofficial and Doyel and Neil at the Brighton Festival 2025 press launch

latestPosts.caption:
We were invited by @anoushkashankarofficial and @brightonfestival to design the Brighton Festival 2025 brochure cover and to do the principal art installation, reflecting on this year’s theme of a New Dawn 

It’s exciting that for the first time in Brighton Festival’s history, the brochure features four different covers—each one part of a larger participatory project where hundreds of people from diverse backgrounds, in India and beyond were invited to draw a ‘new dawn’. This process will continue throughout the festival — here are some of the many explorations.. 

These drawings capture the power and potential of the darkness before daybreak and together form a collective vision of renewal and possibility — A personal, subconscious rendering of hope, renewal and resurgence. 

Inspired by @anoushkashankarofficial album and theme for the festival we explore hope as a utopian impulse. Not passive but active as a creative force that propels individuals towards imagining new futures. In our research, this aligns with practices that are speculative, forward looking or rooted in world building. Each participant works as cartographers of possibility. 

The concept extends beyond the brochure: workshops will take place across Brighton’s schools, public spaces, homes, and festival venues, allowing people to reflect and create their own personal New Dawn. This evolving, participatory act will culminate in an exhibition (May 24–27) at The Old Courtroom and expand internationally with workshops and in a global online canvas, bringing together drawings from around the world. 

In conceiving the idea for the cover we started a process in our studio in Mumbai alongside our team @manasviniapte and @manasvita_maddi . It was then extended to friends, family, schools, etc.

More-so, this wouldn’t have been possible without print artist @manasviniapte who works with us and who managed the project and prints. 

Excited to share more soon alongside @amalaiana 

#brightonfestival #anoushkashankar #howareyoufeeling.studio
